Review and redesign ONLY the Calendar component and its responsive behavior. Do not modify the application header, sidebar, navigation, branding, top bar, user menu, or any other global layout elements.

The desktop calendar is the reference implementation and should remain visually unchanged. Focus exclusively on improving the calendar experience on tablets and mobile devices.

Objectives:

- Maintain visual consistency with the desktop calendar.
- Create a mobile-first calendar experience instead of simply shrinking the desktop version.
- Maximize the usable space dedicated to events and scheduling.
- Reduce empty areas and unnecessary vertical scrolling.
- Ensure the calendar is fully usable on screens below 768px.

Calendar-specific improvements:

1. Responsive Toolbar

- Reorganize calendar controls into compact rows on mobile.
- Keep all existing functionality.
- Prioritize:
  - Create Event
  - Today
  - Previous / Next navigation
  - Current Month/Date
  - View selector
  - Timezone selector

1. Calendar Views

- Month View
- Week View
- Day View
- Agenda View

All views must be fully optimized for touch devices.

1. Mobile Default View

- Automatically use Week View or Agenda View on mobile devices.
- Keep Month View available as an option.

Reason:
Users typically need to see upcoming appointments rather than a full monthly grid.

1. Month View Optimization

- Reduce excessive whitespace.
- Increase information density.
- Use the full screen width.
- Show event indicators inside each day.
- Support:
  - Event count
  - Event dots
  - "+X more" indicators

1. Week View Optimization

- Make Week View the primary mobile scheduling experience.
- Show days in a compact and readable format.
- Allow quick navigation between weeks.
- Display event counts and summaries.

1. Day View Optimization

- Display a clean time-based schedule.
- Support touch-friendly event cards.
- Clearly display appointment times, follow-ups, reminders, and tasks.

1. Agenda View

- Replace the current List view with a modern Agenda view.
- Group events by date.
- Show upcoming activities in chronological order.
- Make this view highly optimized for mobile usage.

Example:

Today
09:00 Consultation
11:30 Follow-up

Tomorrow
14:00 Treatment Review

1. Event Creation UX

- On mobile, event creation should open as a bottom sheet instead of a large desktop modal.
- Minimize required fields initially.
- Allow progressive expansion for advanced details.

1. Empty State
When no events exist:

- Show a meaningful empty state instead of a large blank calendar.
- Include actions such as:
  - Create Event
  - Import Calendar
  - Connect Google Calendar

1. Additional Calendar UX Improvements
Add support for:

- Event color categories
- Quick event filtering
- Calendar source visibility toggles
- Google Calendar synchronization status
- AI scheduling assistance ("Find Best Time")

1. Touch Experience

- Minimum touch target size: 44px.
- No horizontal scrolling.
- No clipped controls.
- Smooth transitions between Month, Week, Day, and Agenda views.
- Optimized for both portrait and landscape orientations.

Success Criteria:

- The calendar feels like a native mobile calendar application.
- Information density is significantly improved.
- Scheduling actions require fewer taps.
- The calendar remains visually consistent with the desktop version.
- Desktop behavior remains unchanged.
- All improvements are isolated to the Calendar module only.
